    <summary>A metapackage to install the recommended tools for maintaining Chocolatey packages</summary>
    <description>## Chocolatey Package Maintenance Toolkit

This metapackage installs the complete, recommended toolset for creating, testing, and maintaining [Chocolatey](https://chocolatey.org) community packages.

### What Gets Installed

| Package | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Visual Studio Code** | Primary editor for authoring `.nuspec`, `chocolateyInstall.ps1`, and other package files |
| **Git** | Version control for managing package source code |
| **GitHub CLI** | Create and manage pull requests and issues from the terminal |
| **PowerShell Extension for VS Code** | Syntax highlighting, IntelliSense, and debugging for PowerShell scripts |
| **Chocolatey Extension for VS Code** | Snippets, linting, and tooling specific to Chocolatey package authoring |
| **Expresso** | Desktop regex builder and tester — useful for writing AU update patterns |

### Who Is This For?

This package targets **Chocolatey Community Repository maintainers** who want a consistent, reproducible development environment. Whether you are onboarding a new machine or helping a new contributor get started, one command is all it takes:

```powershell
choco install maintainertoolkit
```

### Notes

- All dependency versions are pinned to known-good releases. You can upgrade individual tools independently after installation.
- This is a **metapackage** — it contains no binaries of its own; it exists solely to pull in its dependencies.
    </description>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency id="vscode.install" version="1.111.0" />
      <dependency id="git.install" version="2.53.0.2" />
      <dependency id="vscode-powershell" version="2025.4.0" />
      <dependency id="chocolatey-vscode" version="0.7.2" />
      <dependency id="gh" version="2.87.2" />
      <dependency id="expresso" version="3.0.4750" />
    </dependencies>
  </metadata>
  <files>
    <!-- this section controls what actually gets packaged into the Chocolatey package -->
    <file src="tools\**" target="tools" />
  </files>
</package>
